fitPrice = predict(basic_model, newdata=AmesTest8)
holdout_resids = AmesTest8$Price - fitPrice
mean(holdout_resids)
[1] 0.228936
sd(holdout_resids)
[1] 24.87142

The mean of the holdout residuals are quite small and close to zero, which is what we expect from a model that predicts the price fairly well. The standard deviation of about $25,000 is also reasonable given the price ranges of the houses.

qqnorm(holdout_resids)

6.772511 5.525354 4.390197 4.343721 3.369223 3.254552 3.237170 3.108114 3.079827 2.852592

There are a few values in the lower quantile and several values in the upper quantile that have especially large holdout residuals, as shown in the Q-Q plot. The histogram similarly shows a fairly normal distribution of the residuals except for some outliers near the ends. The output above shows their indices in the holdout data. Our model predicted the prices of the houses at indices 170 and 545, which had studentized values of greater than 5, and so we decided to remove them from the dataset later on as we checked the dataset and their prices were indeed abnormally high for their characteristics, coming in at around $535,000 and $612,000 respectively.

crosscor=cor(AmesTest8$Price, fitPrice)
crosscor
[1] 0.9329168
0.8594 - crosscor^2
[1] -0.01093376

The shrinkage is negative which is not terrible because a large shrinkage is bad. Our model is fitting the test data better than the training data, therefore we do not see a need to change this model at this time.

This code uses different step functions using only the categorical variables to produce best models that would predict the price of the houses. Forward selection and stepwise regression both gave the same model with the least number of predictors. We added all of these predictors, namely BasementHt, KitchenQ, GarageType, ExteriorQ, GarageC, LotConfig, HouseStyle, HeatingQC, BasementC, BasementFin, Heating, and GarageQ to our old fancy model to create our new fancy model.

PART 7 : Cross-validation for “fancy” model

testData = AmesTest8

We had to fix up the data a little bit, converting “0” values to the equivalent value of “None”

fitNewPrice = predict(newFancyModel, newdata=testData)
prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading
newHoldout_resids = testData$Price - exp(fitNewPrice)
mean(newHoldout_resids)
[1] 2.922071
sd(newHoldout_resids)
[1] 22.42529
crosscor=cor(testData$Price, exp(fitNewPrice))
crosscor
[1] 0.9463632
0.9036 - crosscor^2
[1] 0.007996614

We now get a really small positive shrinkage of 0.007996614 which is more of what we expect, where the model for the training data explains more variability in the training data than it does for the testing data. But being so small, it also means that our model is doing quite a good job of predicting prices for houses in both datasets. The mean for the residuals has gone up, but the standard deviation has gone down when compared to our basic model, which means the spread of our residuals is smaller which is good. R does give us a warning “prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading”, so we might have some multicollinearity issues.

We decided to tweak our model to get rid of the warning of multicollinearity. It ended up being just trial and error as we took out and put in random categorical predictors until the warning went away. We also ran into issues where the data regarding the house was missing some data for predictors we had in our model (i.e. KitchenQ and BasementC) so we had to take out those predictors as well.
